    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA200-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi talaimakaḷatu kuṟippaṟintu vāyilākap pukka pāṇaṉ kēṭpak kuyavaṉaik kūvi “yiṅṅaṉañ collāyō” eṉṟu kuyavaṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante said to the potter “are you talking like this?”, calling the potter so that the bard could hear who had entered as a mediator knowing the intentions of HER.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA200">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kaṇṇi kaṭṭiya katira vaṉṉa</l>
<l>            voṇkura ṉoccit teriyal cūṭi</l>
<l>            yāṟukiṭan taṉṉa vakaṉeṭun teruviṟ</l>
<l>            cāṟeṉa nuvalu mutuvāy kuyava</l>
<l>            vituvu māṅka ṇuvaṉṟiciṉ mātō </l>
<l>            vāmpa lamaṉṟa tīmperum paḻaṉattup</l>
<l>            poykai yūrkkup pōvō yākik</l>
<l>            kaikavar narampiṟ paṉuvaṟ pāṇaṉ</l>
<l>            ceyta vallal palkuva vaiyeyiṟ</l>
<l>            ṟaitaka lalkuṉ makaḷirivaṉ </l>
<l>            poypoti koṭuñco lōmpumi ṉeṉavē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O potter of old wisdom who talks about [the coming] festival</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the streets wide [and] long like a river gone to rest,</l>
<l rend="indent2">wearing the garland of Nocci with bright ears</l>
<l rend="indent3">resembling ears of grain tied in a chaplet(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṇṇikaṭṭiya</term>: the TL takes this as a lexeme meaning "to bud", and so does T.V.G., only that he reads it to be referring to the unripe state of the grains.</note>,</l>
<l>shouldn't you tell<note place="foot">It is the particle <term xml:lang="ta">mātō</term> which marks the question as rhetorical and ironic in intent and is as thus best rendered by an English negative question.</note> there also this,</l>
<l rend="indent">as you go to the village with [its] pond</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the sweet big paddy fields, thickly grown with white waterlilies?</l>
<l rend="indent">“The much-talking bard with [his] hand-plucked strings,</l>
<l rend="indent2">o you women with sharp teeth [and] beautifully broad hips,</l>
<l rend="indent">beware of his cruel words, a hoard of lies,</l>
<l rend="indent2">that are increasing the unhappiness [already] caused.”<note place="foot">The last four lines seem to be anacoluthic, or at least I for one do not see a way of construing them convincingly, but for once the sense is clear, nevertheless.</note></l>
        </lg>
